  "What is a permutation?": "",
  "Any group of items": "",
  "A factorial calculation": "",
  "A selection of items where order does NOT matter": "",
  "An arrangement of items where order DOES matter": "",
  "A permutation is an ordered arrangement. The order of selection matters, so AB is different from BA.": "",
  "What is a combination?": "",
  "A product of factorials": "",
  "An arrangement where order matters": "",
  "The total number of possible outcomes": "",
  "A combination is a selection where order doesn't matter. Choosing {A, B, C} is the same as {C, B, A}.": "",
  "What is the formula for P(n, r)?": "",
  "nʳ": "",
  "n!/(r!(n−r)!)": "",
  "n!/(n−r)!": "",
  "r!/n!": "",
  "P(n,r) = n!/(n−r)! counts ordered arrangements of r items chosen from n.": "",
  "What is the formula for C(n, r)?": "",
  "nʳ/r": "",
  "n × r": "",
  "C(n,r) = n!/(r!(n−r)!) counts unordered selections of r items from n. It equals P(n,r)/r!.": "",
  "What is a 'permutation with repetition'?": "",
  "Choosing items without regard to order": "",
  "Any arrangement of distinct items": "",
  "Selecting items that can be reused": "",
  "Arranging items where some are identical, using n!/(n₁! · n₂! · ...)": "",
  "When some items are identical (repeated), the number of distinguishable arrangements is n!/(n₁! · n₂! · ...) where nᵢ counts each group of identical items.": "",
  "How do you decide whether a problem requires a permutation or a combination?": "",
  "If the order of selection matters, use a permutation; if not, use a combination": "",
  "Use permutation only for numbers, combination only for letters": "",
  "Use a permutation if n > 10, otherwise use a combination": "",
  "Always use a combination for real-world problems": "",
  "The key distinction: if rearranging the selected items creates a different outcome (like 1st/2nd place), use a permutation. If not (like choosing committee members), use a combination.": "",
  "What is the relationship between P(n, r) and C(n, r)?": "",
  "They are always equal": "",
  "C(n,r) = P(n,r) / r!": "",
  "P(n,r) = C(n,r) / r!": "",
  "P(n,r) = C(n,r) + r!": "",
  "C(n,r) = P(n,r)/r! because combinations remove the r! orderings of each selection that permutations count separately.": "",
  "What does C(n, r) = C(n, n−r) mean?": "",
  "Choosing r items is the same as leaving out n−r items": "",
  "Permutations and combinations are the same": "",
  "The formula only works when r = n/2": "",
  "All combinations are equal": "",
  "This symmetry property means choosing r items from n is equivalent to choosing which n−r items to leave out. For example, C(10,3) = C(10,7).": "",
  "What does 'distinguishable' mean in the context of permutations?": "",
  "Only the first item matters": "",
  "All items are unique and can be told apart": "",
  "The arrangement cannot be rearranged": "",
  "All items are identical": "",
  "Distinguishable means each item is unique and can be identified separately. When items are indistinguishable (identical), we divide by the repeated factorial.": "",
  "What is a 'circular permutation'?": "",
  "A combination of circular shapes": "",
  "Any arrangement of items in a line": "",
  "A permutation that uses pi": "",
  "An arrangement of items in a circle where rotations are considered the same": "",
  "In circular permutations, arrangements that differ only by rotation are identical. The number of circular permutations of n items is (n−1)!.": "",
